{"text": " You know that it's cold here in South Florida when it starts raining iguanas. It's currently about 36 degrees here in South Florida and since iguanas are cold-blooded and they sleep up in the trees, when they get too cold, they no longer can hang on and they end up falling to the ground. Typically it's so warm that this doesn't happen, but every once in a while we get a cold front and then the iguanas start falling straight out of the trees so you can pretty much walk across any little body of water and you'll end up seeing frozen iguanas if it's around 35 to 36 degrees. Here's another one and another one and another one. Imagine getting ready for work and backing up and just finding this in your driveway. Even though they look like they're dead, once they start to warm back up, a lot of them will pop right back to life. But a lot of times because they fall into the road, they end up getting run over. So these cold fronts really do a number on their population. Green iguanas are actually an invasive species here in South Florida but they do get the nickname chicken of the trees because they taste delicious. So if you see iguanas raining out of the trees, now you know why and if you're in the mood for tacos, maybe give them a try. And until next time, get outside and see what you can find.", "segments": [{"id": 0, "seek": 0, "start": 0.0, "end": 1.76, "text": " You know that it's cold here in South Florida", "tokens": [50364, 509, 458, 300, 309, 311, 3554, 510, 294, 4242, 9117, 50452], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11005037911930439, "compression_ratio": 1.8087774294670846, "no_speech_prob": 0.012503085657954216}, {"id": 1, "seek": 0, "start": 1.76, "end": 3.4, "text": " when it starts raining iguanas.", "tokens": [50452, 562, 309, 3719, 18441, 8508, 6139, 296, 13, 50534], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11005037911930439, "compression_ratio": 1.8087774294670846, "no_speech_prob": 0.012503085657954216}, {"id": 2, "seek": 0, "start": 3.4, "end